data.content:
Yes! For simple inline data, use `[DataRow]` — it's cleaner and type-safe:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

If you need **computed/complex data** (where `DataRow` won't work since it requires compile-time constants), MSTest v3.4+ supports **typed `DynamicData`** to avoid `object[]`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Summary of options:**

| Approach | Best for |
|---|---|
| `[DataRow]` | Simple constant values |
| `DynamicData` with tuples | Computed data, type safety |
| `DynamicData` with `object[]` | Legacy / mixed types |

`DataRow` is the go-to for your example. Use typed `DynamicData` when you need runtime-generated test cases.
